Incident Management Platforms

Incident management is the process of identifying, analyzing, and resolving cyber incidents. Organizations usually receive a huge number of alerts every single day. Thus, it is vital to establish and follow a process so that all incidents are handled efficiently.

Defenders use incident management platforms to help them follow the process and keep things organized. These platforms increase response speed and ensure the team will notice critical steps during investigations.

 

Example Workflow


Incident management platforms utilize workflows and playbooks to structure what actions to take at each phase. In a nutshell, a workflow is a sequence of connected steps in the life cycle of an incident, such as logging, categorization, investigation, recovery, review, and closure. These platforms usually provide an integrated ticketing system to receive requests, assign them and track their status.

A famous incident management platform is TheHive Project.

 

According to TheHive Project:

"TheHive is a scalable 4-in-1 open source and free Security Incident Response Platform, tightly integrated with MISP (Malware Information Sharing Platform), designed to make life easier for SOCs, CSIRTs, CERTs, and any information security practitioner dealing with security incidents that need to be investigated and acted upon swiftly."

 

Figure

Incident management platforms are not limited to documenting incident details and streamlining the response process. For example, the Cortex project offers additional options to improve the incident management process.

 

The Cortex project page describes the project as follows:

"Cortex solves two common problems frequently encountered by SOCs, CSIRTs, and security researchers in the course of threat intelligence, digital forensics, and incident response:

  • How to analyze observables they have collected, at scale, by querying a single tool instead of several?
  • How to actively respond to threats and interact with the constituency and other teams?"


It's worth mentioning that incident management is not an exclusive security thing. You will probably see other departments in your organization, such as IT and networking, use incident management platforms to track their operations.

In addition to incident management platforms, there are a bunch of technical tools that responders rely on to do their job, such as:

  • Packet sniffers.
  • Forensics image capturing tools such as FTK imager.
  • Forensics analysis tools such as Autopsy and EnCase.
  • Smart and non-smartphones for out-of-band communications.
  • Removable media to store collected pieces of evidence.
  • Network tap to inspect network traffic.
